{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606869"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:17:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:17:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15937"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15937"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8628"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58311"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8673"},{"type":"tags","id":"8677"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20662"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20666"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring kidney development, different embryological tissues interact to form the functional units of the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of nephron structures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ureteric bud forms all nephron structures independently","Metanephric mesoderm forms collecting ducts while ureteric bud forms nephron tubules","Metanephric mesoderm forms glomeruli and nephron tubules while ureteric bud forms collecting ducts","Neural crest cells form glomeruli while mesoderm forms tubular structures","Intermediate mesoderm forms all nephron structures independently"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe development of the nephron involves two key embryological structures working together. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emetanephric mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the renal corpuscle (glomerulus) and the tubular components of the nephron, including the proximal tubule, loop of Henle, and distal tubule. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric bud\u003C/strong\u003E, which branches from the mesonephric duct, forms the collecting ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe interaction between these tissues is crucial - the ureteric bud induces the metanephric mesoderm to form nephrons, while the metanephric mesoderm signals the ureteric bud to branch repeatedly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteric bud forms all nephron structures independently\u003C/strong\u003E - This ignores the essential role of metanephric mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetanephric mesoderm forms collecting ducts while ureteric bud forms nephron tubules\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the reverse of the correct developmental pattern\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells form glomeruli while mesoderm forms tubular structures\u003C/strong\u003E - Neural crest cells are not involved in nephron formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermediate mesoderm forms all nephron structures independently\u003C/strong\u003E - While metanephric mesoderm derives from intermediate mesoderm, the ureteric bud is also required\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The nephron develops from two distinct embryological structures: the metanephric mesoderm and the ureteric bud","The metanephric mesoderm forms the renal corpuscle (glomerulus) and tubular components of the nephron","The ureteric bud forms the collecting ducts and induces nephron formation through reciprocal signalling"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58311"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15937"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58311"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:48:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T09:50:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8628"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72841"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type